deep_patterns_sample.description: The data follows a pattern where the harmonic mean of each pair of consecutive terms converges to the golden ratio. This pattern is a deeper property of the Fibonacci sequence, which is itself a well-known pattern in the data.
deep_patterns_sample.mathematical_formula: ∀n > 1, 2 / (1 / F(n) + 1 / F(n+1)) → φ as n → ∞, where F(n) is the nth Fibonacci number and φ is the golden ratio
deep_patterns_sample.why_not_obvious: Humans often focus on the simple recursive formula of the Fibonacci sequence and overlook more complex statistical properties, such as the behavior of the harmonic mean.

deep_patterns_sample.description: Upon analyzing the second-order differences of the sequence (i.e., the differences of the differences), it becomes apparent that this derived sequence exhibits properties of stationarity, meaning its statistical properties, such as the mean and variance, remain constant over time. This is not immediately obvious from the original sequence, which grows rapidly.
deep_patterns_sample.mathematical_formula: Let Δ²F(n) = F(n+2) - 2F(n+1) + F(n). Then, E[Δ²F(n)] = constant and Var(Δ²F(n)) = constant for all n.
deep_patterns_sample.why_not_obvious: The rapid growth of the Fibonacci sequence can distract from deeper statistical properties of derived sequences, such as second-order differences, which require more advanced analysis to uncover.

deep_patterns_sample.description: The growth rate of the sequence, when measured in terms of the logarithm of the ratio of successive terms, approaches a constant value. This is related to the asymptotic behavior of the Fibonacci sequence but provides a different insight into its growth properties.
deep_patterns_sample.mathematical_formula: lim(n→∞) log(F(n+1) / F(n)) = log(φ), where φ is the golden ratio
deep_patterns_sample.why_not_obvious: While the Fibonacci sequence's relation to the golden ratio is well-known, analyzing its growth through the lens of logarithmic ratios reveals a nuanced aspect of its asymptotic behavior that might not be immediately apparent.
